### Interpolation of PnP-DM

In this section, we formally introduce the interpolation of PnP-DM. We consider the case where the coupling strength \(\rho\) is constant, i.e. \(\rho_{k}\equiv\rho\) and make the following assumption.

**Assumption A.1**.: _There exists a unique \(t^{*}\) such that \(\sigma(t^{*})=\rho\)._

This assumption is satisfied for common diffusion models. Popular choices of the noise level schedule include \(\sigma(t)=t\) or \(\sigma(t)=\sqrt{t}\), which are monotonically increasing functions of \(t\). We first present two propositions showing that the two steps in SGS can be implemented by running two SDEs.

**Proposition A.2** (Brownian bridge for the likelihood step).: _For iteration \(k\) with iterate \(\bm{x}^{(k)}\), the likelihood step of SGS is equivalent to solving the following SDE from \(t=0\) to \(t=1\):_

\[\mathrm{d}\bm{x}_{t}=\rho^{2}\nabla\log\phi_{t}(\bm{x}_{t})\mathrm{d}t+\rho \mathrm{d}\bm{w}_{t}\] (9)

_where \(\bm{x}_{0}=\bm{x}^{(k)}\) and \(\phi_{t}(\bm{x}):=\int\exp[-f(\bm{z};\bm{y})-\frac{1}{2\rho^{2}(1-t)}\|\bm{x}- \bm{z}\|_{2}^{2}]\mathrm{d}\bm{z}\)._

Proof.: This proposition is due to the Brownian bridge construction presented in Lemma 4 of [79]. This SDE satisfies that \(p(\bm{x}_{1}|\bm{x}_{0})\propto\exp\left(-f(\bm{x}_{1};\bm{y})-\frac{1}{2\rho ^{2}}\|\bm{x}_{0}-\bm{x}_{1}\|_{2}^{2}\right)\). Therefore, solving (9) from \(t=0\) to \(t=1\) is equivalent to taking a likelihood step. 

**Proposition A.3** (EDM reverse diffusion for the prior step).: _For iteration \(k\) with iterate \(\bm{z}^{(k)}\), the prior step of SGS is equivalent to solving the following SDE from \(t=t^{*}\) to \(t=0\):_

\[\mathrm{d}\bm{x}_{t}=\left[u(t)\bm{x}_{t}-v(t)^{2}\nabla\log p_{t}\left(\bm{x }_{t}\right)\right]\mathrm{d}t+v(t)\mathrm{d}\bar{\bm{w}}_{t}\] (10)

_where \(\bm{x}_{t^{*}}=s(t^{*})\bm{z}^{(k)}\), \(u(t):=\frac{\dot{s}(t)}{s(t)}\), \(v(t):=s(t)\sqrt{2\dot{\sigma}(t)\sigma(t)}\), and \(p_{t}\) is the distribution of \(s(t)\bm{x}+s(t)\sigma(t)\bm{\epsilon}\) with \(\bm{x}\) following the prior distribution \(p(\bm{x})\propto\exp(-g(\bm{x}))\) and \(\bm{\epsilon}\sim\mathcal{N}(\bm{0},\bm{I})\)._

Proof.: First note that (10) is exactly (7) written in terms of \(u(t)\) and \(v(t)\). We know that the (10) is the reverse SDE of the following SDE

\[\mathrm{d}\bm{x}_{t}=u(t)\bm{x}_{t}\mathrm{d}t+v(t)\mathrm{d}\bm{w}_{t}.\] (11)

where \(\bm{x}_{0}\sim p(\bm{x})\) and \(p_{t}\) is the marginal distribution of \(\bm{x}_{t}\). As we showed in the main text, it holds for (11) that

\[p(\bm{x}_{0}|\bm{x}_{t})\propto\exp\left(-g(\bm{x}_{0})-\frac{1}{2\sigma(t)^ {2}}\|\bm{x}_{0}-\bm{x}_{t}/s(t)\|_{2}^{2}\right).\]

As (10) is the time-reversed process of (11), they share the same path distribution and thus the same conditional distribution \(p(\bm{x}_{0}|\bm{x}_{t})\). So, if we set \(\bm{x}_{t^{*}}=s(t^{*})\bm{z}^{(k)}\), we have that

\[p(\bm{x}_{0}|\bm{x}_{t^{*}})\propto\exp\left(-g(\bm{x}_{0})-\frac{1}{2\sigma(t ^{*})^{2}}\|\bm{x}_{0}-\bm{z}^{(k)}\|_{2}^{2}\right)\propto\exp\left(-g(\bm{x }_{0})-\frac{1}{2\rho^{2}}\|\bm{x}_{0}-\bm{z}^{(k)}\|_{2}^{2}\right),\]

which is the desired conditional distribution of the prior step. Therefore, solving (10) from \(t=t^{*}\) to \(t=0\) is equivalent to taking a prior step. 

Due to Proposition A.2 and Proposition A.3, the SDEs (9) and (10) implement the two desired conditional distributions in SGS. In PnP-DM, the prior step involves a network that approximates the score function of the prior distribution, i.e. \(\bm{s}_{t}\approx\nabla\log p_{t}\), so the continuous-time process for the actual update is

\[\mathrm{d}\bm{x}_{t}=\left[u(t)\bm{x}_{t}-v(t)^{2}\bm{s}_{t}\left(\bm{x}_{t} \right)\right]\mathrm{d}t+v(t)\mathrm{d}\bar{\bm{w}}_{t}.\] (12)

We can then interpolate PnP-DM by considering a dynamic that alternates between running (9) and (12).

Since each likelihood step takes \(1\) unit of time and each prior step takes \(t^{*}\) unit of time, the total time of the interpolating process for \(K\) iterations of PnP-DM is \(T:=K(t^{*}+1)\). We use \(\tau\) to denote the time that has elapsed from initializing PnP-DM with \(\bm{x}^{(0)}\). We define \(\{\nu_{\tau}\}\) and \(\{\pi_{\tau}\}\) as the distributions at time \(\tau\) of the non-stationary process initialized at \(\bm{x}^{(0)}\sim\nu_{0}^{X}\) (Figure 3 top) and the stationary process initialized at \(\bm{x}^{(0)}\sim\pi^{X}\) (Figure 3 bottom), respectively. Therefore, we have * \(\nu_{\tau}=\nu_{k}^{X}\), \(\pi_{\tau}=\pi^{X}\) for \(\tau=k(t^{*}+1)\) with \(k=0,\cdots,K\), and
* \(\nu_{\tau}=\nu_{k}^{Z}\), \(\pi_{\tau}=\pi^{Z}\) for \(\tau=k(t^{*}+1)+1\) with \(k=0,\cdots,K-1\).

