## Appendix C Technical details of PnP-DM

### Likelihood step

Linear forward model and Gaussian noiseAs we showed in the main paper, in case of linear forward models and Gaussian noise, the likelihood step is

\[\pi^{Z|X=\bm{x}}=\mathcal{N}(\bm{m}(\bm{x}),\bm{\Lambda}^{-1})\]

where \(\bm{\Lambda}:=\bm{A}^{T}\bm{\Sigma}^{-1}\bm{A}+\frac{1}{\rho^{2}}\bm{I}\) and \(\bm{m}(\bm{x}):=\bm{\Lambda}^{-1}(\bm{A}^{T}\bm{\Sigma}^{-1}\bm{y}+\frac{1}{ \rho^{2}}\bm{x})\). The bottleneck here is that both the mean and the covariance involve the matrix inverse \(\bm{\Lambda}^{-1}\), which can be prohibitive to compute directly for high-dimensional problems. Nevertheless, the computational cost can be significantly alleviated when the noise is i.i.d. Gaussian, i.e. \(\bm{\Sigma}=\sigma_{\bm{y}}^{2}\bm{I}\), and \(\bm{A}\) can be efficiently decomposed. For example, if one can efficiently calculate the SVD of the forward model \(\bm{A}\), i.e. \(\bm{A}=\bm{U}\bm{S}\bm{V}^{T}\), one can find the Cholesky decomposition of \(\bm{\Lambda}^{-1}\) as

\[\bm{\Lambda}^{-1}=\bm{L}\bm{L}^{T}\quad\text{where}\quad\bm{L}:=\bm{V}\left( \frac{1}{\sigma^{2}}\bm{S}^{2}+\frac{1}{\rho^{2}}\bm{I}\right)^{-1/2}.\]

Since \(\bm{S}\) is a diagonal matrix, the second term can be calculated with only \(O(n)\) complexity. Then, leveraging the property of multivariate Gaussian distribution, we can sample \(\bm{\eta}\sim\mathcal{N}(\bm{0},\bm{I})\) and calculate \(\bm{z}=\bm{m}(\bm{x})+\bm{L}\bm{\eta}\) as a sample that exactly follows the target Gaussian distribution \(\mathcal{N}(\bm{m}(\bm{x}),\bm{\Lambda}^{-1})\). An analogous derivation with Fourier transform can be done when \(\bm{A}\) is a circulant convolution matrix.

