### Prior step

The EDM frameworkWe formally introduce the EDM formulation [37] using our notations. The forward diffusion process is defined as the following linear Ito SDE

\[\mathrm{d}\bm{x}_{t}=u(t)\bm{x}_{t}\mathrm{d}t+v(t)\mathrm{d}\bm{w}_{t},\] (23)

where \(u(t):\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}\), \(v(t):\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}\) are the drift and diffusion coefficients. The generative process is the time-reversed version of (23). According to [2], it is another Ito SDE of the form

\[\mathrm{d}\bm{x}_{t}=\left[u(t)\bm{x}_{t}-v(t)^{2}\nabla_{\bm{x}_{t}}\log p_{t }(\bm{x}_{t})\right]\mathrm{d}t+v(t)\mathrm{d}\bar{\bm{w}}_{t},\] (24)

where \(p_{t}(\bm{x}_{t})\) is the marginal distribution of \(\bm{x}_{t}\). There also exists a reverse probability flow ODE

\[\mathrm{d}\bm{x}_{t}=\left[u(t)\bm{x}_{t}-\frac{1}{2}v(t)^{2}\nabla_{\bm{x}_{ t}}\log p_{t}(\bm{x}_{t})\right]\mathrm{d}t,\] (25)

which shares the same marginal distributions as (24). Based on (23), we have

\[p(\bm{x}_{t}|\bm{x}_{0})=\mathcal{N}(s(t)\bm{x}_{0},s(t)^{2}\sigma(t)^{2}\bm{ I})\]

where \(s(t):=\exp\left(\int_{0}^{t}u(\xi)\mathrm{d}\xi\right)\) and \(\sigma(t):=\sqrt{\int_{0}^{t}\frac{v(\xi)^{2}}{s(\xi)^{2}}\mathrm{d}\xi}\). We also have \(\bm{x}_{t}/s(t)\sim p(\bm{x};\sigma(t))\) where \(p(\bm{x};\sigma(t))\) is the distribution obtained by adding i.i.d. Gaussian noise of standard deviation \(\sigma(t))\) to the prior data. The idea of the EDM formulation is to write the reverse diffusion directly in terms of the scaling and noise level of \(\bm{x}_{t}\) with respect to \(\bm{x}_{0}\), which are more important than the drift and diffusion coefficients. With the relations between \(u(t)\), \(v(t)\), \(p_{t}\) and \(s(t)\), \(\sigma(t)\), \(p(\cdot;\sigma(t))\), we can rewrite (24) and (25) as

\[\mathrm{d}\bm{x}_{t}=\left[\frac{\dot{s}(t)}{s(t)}\bm{x}_{t}-2s(t)^{2}\dot{ \sigma}(t)\sigma(t)\nabla_{\bm{x}_{t}}\log p\left(\frac{\bm{x}_{t}}{s(t)}; \sigma(t)\right)\right]\mathrm{d}t+s(t)\sqrt{2\dot{\sigma}(t)\sigma(t)} \mathrm{d}\bar{\bm{w}}_{t}\] (26)

and

\[\mathrm{d}\bm{x}_{t}=\left[\frac{\dot{s}(t)}{s(t)}\bm{x}_{t}-s(t)^{2}\dot{ \sigma}(t)\sigma(t)\nabla_{\bm{x}_{t}}\log p\left(\frac{\bm{x}_{t}}{s(t)}; \sigma(t)\right)\right]\mathrm{d}t.\] (27)

Note that (26) is precisely the SDE (7) we considered for the prior step. Finally, due to the Tweedie's formula [24], we can approximate \(\nabla_{\bm{x}_{t}}\log p\left(\,\cdot\,;\sigma(t)\right)\) by a denoiser \([D_{\theta}(\,\cdot\,;\sigma(t))-\,\cdot\,]/\sigma(t)^{2}\) trained to minimize the \(\ell_{2}\) error of a denoising objective. Substituting the score function by the approximation with the denoiser and using the chain rule, we can further rewrite (26) and (27) as

\[\mathrm{d}\bm{x}_{t}=\left[\left(\frac{2\dot{\sigma}(t)}{\sigma(t)}+\frac{ \dot{s}(t)}{s(t)}\right)\bm{x}_{t}-\frac{2\dot{\sigma}(t)s(t)}{\sigma(t)}D_{ \theta}\left(\frac{\bm{x}_{t}}{s(t)};\sigma(t)\right)\right]\mathrm{d}t+s(t) \sqrt{2\dot{\sigma}(t)\sigma(t)}\mathrm{d}\bar{\bm{w}}_{t}\] (28)

and

\[\mathrm{d}\bm{x}_{t}=\left[\left(\frac{\dot{\sigma}(t)}{\sigma(t)}+\frac{ \dot{s}(t)}{s(t)}\right)\bm{x}_{t}-\frac{\dot{\sigma}(t)s(t)}{\sigma(t)}D_{ \theta}\left(\frac{\bm{x}_{t}}{s(t)};\sigma(t)\right)\right]\mathrm{d}t.\] (29)

